 TCP and UDP

These are two main protocols used to send data over a network. They sit at the Transport Layer (Layer 4) of the OSI model.

---

 1️⃣ TCP – Transmission Control Protocol

 What it is: A protocol that ensures data is sent reliably and in order.
 Layman Example: Sending a registered letter – you get confirmation when it’s delivered.
 
 IT Example:
   SSH (secure remote login)
   HTTP / HTTPS (web traffic)
   FTP (file transfer)
 Characteristics:
   Connection-oriented (establishes a connection first)
   Reliable delivery (retransmits if lost)
   Ordered packets

---

 2️⃣ UDP – User Datagram Protocol

 What it is: A protocol that sends data fast, but without guaranteeing delivery.
 Layman Example: Sending a postcard – it may arrive, but no confirmation.
 
 IT Example:
   DNS (domain name lookups)
   DHCP (IP assignment)
   Streaming videos / VoIP
 Characteristics:

   Connectionless (no handshake)
   No guarantee of delivery
   Fast and lightweight



| Feature     | TCP                 | UDP                  |
| ----------- | ------------------- | -------------------- |
| Reliability | ✅ Guaranteed        | ❌ Not guaranteed     |
| Order       | ✅ Packets in order  | ❌ No order guarantee |
| Connection  | Connection-oriented | Connectionless       |
| Speed       | Slower              | Faster               |
| Examples    | SSH, HTTP, FTP      | DNS, DHCP, Streaming |




few Protocols list under TCP & UDP :

